content.description: One of the easier routes on the Kenticle. Plenty of holds and good jugs when you need them, plus the giant buckets in the center.
content.protection: Five bolts, but they're set for different routes and are hard to reach, so it might be better as a toprope from the blue or gray routes' anchors next to it.
content.location: Right side of the east wall, yellow holds.

content.description: A steep, narrow-to-wide tiered crack with some face pockets and holds. Strenuous crack climbing, plus knowing when to lieback and where to place feet, is the key.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a bolted anchor with loweroffs.
content.location: Northwest side, using only the wall features and no artificial holds.

content.description: Boulder around the entire Kenticle using only the wall features, at about 5-10 feet off the ground. Fairly easy in some spots, but the corners are definitely the cruxes and some involve some downclimbing. Good when the bouldering wall isn't providing enough pump due to the low height.
content.location: Generally I start at the crack on the east side.

content.description: Looks easier than it is - most of the holds are crimpy and slopey. More pumpy than most of the routes, and it's a fun lead.
content.protection: Five bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners.
content.location: Yellow route on the left side of the west face.

content.description: The hardest fake-hold route on the Kenticle. Small holds and a bulge in the middle make this a pumpy face climb.
content.protection: 6 bolts and a two bolt anchor with two carabiners.
content.location: Orange-hold route next to the southeast corner.

content.description: Few holds on this route, making some wrap-around arm movements necessary. A large blue hold 2/3 of the way up is hugely loose, making a very insecure foot hold. Also, you either have to reach around where you can't see on the right or where it's a long reach on the left to clip, so not a very enjoyable lead.
content.protection: You can either use the four bolts of the west side green or the six bolts of the east side orange. Best toproped.
content.location: Blue holds on the south side.

content.description:
Tricky ascent with mostly small crimps for holds. Sparseness is the rule of the day; involves some long reaches and good footwork.

Since the route starts in the center of the formation (following one line of bolts) but then moves right to another line, toproping from one of the other routes' anchors may be preferable.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners.
content.location: There's two yellow routes on the west side, but this one is farther to the right.

content.description: Many routes at the Kenticle are well-set to involve necessary use of the features on the wall, but this is a slight exception. Nice mid-range route with some thoughtful moves, but no real difficult crux.
content.protection: 4 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two non-locking carabiners. The only route without a first bolt clippable from the ground or first move; it's about 10-15 feet off the deck.
content.location: On the west (back) side of the Kenticle. Farthest south route on the actual west side, and it's all bright green.

content.description: Clustered-together bulging gray holds start this climb, then all the holds disappear, forcing you to use the crimps and pockets in the center of the wall. A bit strenuous on the fingers, but the amount of sidepulls and possible jams in the crack to the left make it a fair 5.8.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners, like all the Kenticle routes.
content.location: Gray route to the right of the big crack and the hole. Uses the same bolts as the east-side wall features route.

content.description: Less-than-vertical thin edging route. Delightful sequence of moves that's heavy on footwork and finger strength; deciding to go sidepulls or crimps higher up is the crux, and the decision depends on your individual strengths. Slightly harder than the east side crack but maybe not so pumpy.
content.protection: No bolts on this side, so unless you are very adventurous and want to clip blindly around the right side, this is toprope only.
content.location: South side of the Kenticle; use only the features and no artificial holds.

content.description: Very few holds on this muddy green route, but they're mostly nice jugs. The trick is to find pockets and smears for the feet under the overhangs to push up to the next hold.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners.
content.location: The brownish-green route near the northwest corner.

content.description: Wall on, all holds off. Climb the Kenticle using only the wall features, no bolted holds! Feels easy for the first 10 feet, then some creativity is required to get you past the middle section. Crimps will take you the rest of the way to the "highest point in Kent". Cool route.
content.protection: 5 bolts and chains at the top with two carabiners.
content.location: East side (closest to the parking lot). Follows the large crack over the hole in the wall, then the blanker crimpy face above it with sidepulls from the crack.

content.description: Interesting route on the west side. Doesn't involve getting too pumped, but some thoughtful route-setting makes you use some pockets part of the way up. The crux is moving over the second overhang before there's any holds on the right side of the corner.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two non-locking carabiners.
content.location: Brown route on the west or back side of the Kenticle.

content.description: Definitely has some easy jugs, but when those disappear in favor of some rounded and wrong-way-facing holds is the crux. Wide foot moves in the mini-dihedral are the key.
content.protection: 5 bolts and a two-bolt anchor with two carabiners.
content.location: Route that moves around the east side/northeast corner with blue holds.

pathTokens: Kent East Hill Skate Park (AKA The Kenticle)
